aw preclude them from doing so. This new evidence shows how the current law does not reflect social understandings of what makes a wedding meaningful. As recommended by the Law Commission, reform is urgently needed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMarriage lawzEngland. 0aMarriage lawzWales. 0aMarriage servicezEnglandvCase studies. 0aMarriage servicezWalesvCase studies. 7aLAW / Family Law / Marriage.2bisacsh1 aAkhtar, Rajnaara C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aBlake, Sharon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z97831111967940 cprintz978152923047540uhttps://doi.org/10.56687/9781529230499?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781529230499zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781529230499/original  a978-3-11-119679-4 Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA